  "response": "Whether the Koh-i-Noor diamond was a gift is a complex and controversial issue with different perspectives.\n\n*   **British Perspective:** Some argue that the diamond was given to Queen Victoria by the East India Company as a voluntary surrender after the Second Anglo-Sikh War. They maintain it was a legitimate transfer of ownership.\n\n*   **Indian Perspective:** Many Indians believe the diamond was acquired through coercion or theft. They argue that the East India Company took advantage of a vulnerable situation and that the diamond rightfully belongs to India. Some point to the fact that the child king, Duleep Singh, who gave the diamond, was under British control at the time.\n\n*   **Other Claims:** Pakistan and Afghanistan have also claimed ownership of the diamond, citing different historical periods and rulers.\n\nUltimately, there is no clear consensus on whether the Koh-i-Noor was a gift or not. The historical context, power dynamics, and differing interpretations of events make it a subject of ongoing debate.",
